e for a gentle or inoffensive person, from Middle English <i>cade</i> ‘young animal left by its mother and brought up by hand as a domestic pet’. In southern England, <i>cad</i> is found in dialects, meaning ‘youngest and smallest of a family of any kind’.","French (also <b>Cadé</b>): topographic name from <i>cade</i> ‘juniper’ (from Latin <i>catanus</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadd","meanings":["English: variant of   Cade  ."]},{"name":"Caddy","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Dorset): perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Caddy</i>, a pet form of Old English <i>Cada</i> (see   Cade  )."]},{"name":"Cadman","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>cade</i> ‘barrel used for herring or other fish’ + <i>man</i>, perhaps a metonymic occupational name denoting a maker of casks.","occupational name meaning ‘servant of a man named <i>Cade</i>’ (see   Cade  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomasine","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: A twin; Thomasine is a female version."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":28,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":101,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisd